description.text:
J (6 years old) drew a fishie which we photographed, traced, extruded and transferred into a cookie cutter STL file, using free software. Printed at Auckland City Library, it took about 30 minutes. Instructions attached, cookies to follow.
EDIT: added v2, with some 'improvements' to make for a better cutter & truer likeness of the original drawing.
  • Eyes and mouth! These will indent your fishie with a lovable fishie expression, so long as your dough is over 2mm thick.
  • Cutter is now 9mm high (allows for thicker dough), and thinner (sharper).
  • I've generally lined up the base & cutter a bit better than before.

• Pen & Paper.
  • scanner or digital camera
  • A computer.
  • Access to 3D printer. I'm gonna use one at the city library

description.header: Steps to create a similar design
description.text:
• Go to the internet, install 'inkscape' ( http://www.inkscape.org/ ), 'OpenSCAD' ( http://www.openscad.org/ ), and the 'Inscape to OpenSCAD converter' ( http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:25036 ). These tools are all open source and cross-platform (Linux/Mac/Win), yay!
  • Draw a simple but awesome drawing using the vastness of your creative being. This is the most important part.
  • Photograph the drawing (scanner would be better if you have one).
  • Using Inkscape's Bezier Curve tool I traced around the drawing, and then scaled the tracing down to an appropriate size for a cookie. About 10cm long I think.
  • Still in Inkscape, copy & paste 4 versions of that tracing.
    i. A 'cutter inner line', scaled down to 98%, and then manually tweaked to be consistently inside the original line.
    ii. A 'cutter outer line', scaled up to 102%, then manually tweaked to be consistently just outside the original line.
    iii. A 'base inner line, scaled down to 90%, tweaked as above.
    iv. A 'base outer line', scaled up to 110%, tweaked as above.
  • For each of these lines, select the path and export to SCAD (Inscape menu Extensions > Generate from Path > Paths to OpenSCAD). Choose an appropriate name for each path.
  • Now, take my .scad file, open it in OpenSCAD, and see how it creates a fishy preview
  • For each of your 4 generated files (innerbase/outerbase/innercutter/outercutter):
    i. open the generated file in a text editor, alongside the OpenSCAD window if possible.
    ii. In the generated file, find the really long line beginning 'polygon('. Copy that whole line to the clipboard.
    iii. Now in OpenSCAD, find the equivalent line beginning polygon. There are 4 of these, and each is preceded with a 'module xxx' line. Find the one matching your generated file name, and replace that 'polygon' line with the contents of your clipboard. (Select the line, then Paste)
  • Save the file in OpenSCAD, then hit 'F5' (or use the menu Design > Compile). You should see your cutter take shape. You can modify the 2 height values for the base and cutter if you like.
  • Now to export it, hit 'F6' (compile & render), and then export to STL file (menu: Design > Export as STL ... )
  • Print that STL file. We printed using 'Repetier Host' software on Linux, as provided by the library. There were a couple of options to set for extrusion, but not much. I guess those options depend on the printer.
  • Make cookies. Gingerbread seems to be the best bet to maintain the best shape and not fall apart. We haven't tried yet.
  • EAT COOKIE NUM NUM.

If you make your own screws take a 3mm rod from the hardware store.
If available tkae the threaded rod cut them to the length you need.
If threaded rods are not available take the smooth rod an put the treads on it.
It's a matter of minutes.
.

http://www.nmri.go.jp/eng/khirata/metalwork/basic/bolt/index_e.html
.
When you need a threaded rod of i.E. 80mm length ist ok to work out the thread on both ends only.
Threads of 10-15mm length each should cover all situations where nuts (used as screwheads) are sitting flat on surfaces or sunken in the holes.
Add hatnuts or selflocking nuts or make your own caps for regular nuts.
If you make the setup permanently it's adviced to lock the regular nuts with a drop of glue (Locktite or similar).

title: Case for Minim OSD with Team-kv mods

description.text: Another case for the minim-OSD, but this one accomodates the slightly wider board used on the OSD that sports the Team-kv modifications (such as the OSD from Witespy or a few choice sellers on Ebay), which add an additional row of pin connections across the top of the board.  I am not actually using these pins yet, so the original case does not offer external access to them.  However, I have included a separate top which does provide a slot openning for access to these pins.

Designed in Viacad and printed on Printrbot printer. Design is shamelessly borrowed from and/or inspired-by the fine design by dennisbaldwin. I highly recommend viewing his fine how-to videos on Youtube... easily some of the best and most useful videos you'll find there.
I print these with .22mm layer height and 25% infill, though I suspect most any values will work well. It doesn't need to be exceedingly strong and we do want to keep it light in weight.

This is a push vice to center your work on your CNC bed. It prevents the work from moving sideways. Solid infill is recommended. If you plan to use this for heavy duty, you should use the metal version instead of plastic.
When open, the vice is a cube. When closed, the top section moves against the work and secures it on that side. If you want to secure a square sheet of metal, you should use 4 such vices, one vice for each side of the square.
This version uses a M5 screw/washer/nut to bolt the vice to your CNC bed. It has 5mm of travel against the secured work.

Bolt a M5 screw to your T-Slot CNC bed.
Slide the bottom of the vice in.
Slide the top of the vice in.
Slide a M5 washer in.
Run a M5 nut at the end of the screw.
Place the vice near your work, touching it.
Tighten the M5 nut until your work is secured.

A simple object that can appear as a circle, a square, or a triangle, depending on the direction from which it is viewed.
I made this after listening to some friends discussing the 3-in-1 nature of the Christian Trinity - One deity that manifests as the Father, Son, and Holy Spirit.
Regardless of whether the theological application is appropriate or not, the thing can serve as an object lesson in how something can be interpreted in different ways, depending on your point of view. The objects horizontal cross section is an ellipse. At the base, the major and minor axis = 1. As Z increases from 0 to 1, the major axis holds constant at 1 while the minor axis decreases linearly to zero.

description.text: Superceded by http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:59352 I have been using my quikfit compact extruder for many months and prints and finally it blew apart tonight and fortunately I still had a spare but that is my last one and I really need an extruder suitable for hotter temperatures for nylon and ABS so this extruder will use an aluminium plate below the extruder to hold a J-head hot end. The alloy plate will remain solid at higher temperatures and should have better print quality for longer. There are two versions here, one is just the extruder and idler and the other also has my 45/11 gear set for a complete extruder in a tray for printing. When finished it looks very similar to the one in the photos on my OB1 printing out the new version.

Print it out at .25mm layer height, 40% fill, 2 perimeters and 2 tops & bottoms.
Drill out the motor mount holes and the idler hinge hole with a 3mm drill.
Drill out the base mount holes with a 4mm drill.
Run a 3.5mm drill through the filament hole.
Drill out the small gear middle to 5mm.
Drill out the large gear centre to 8mm. Cut away the built-in support for the idler with a razor blade or just snap it off with your fingers.
Cut a 20mm long section of 8mm rod for the idler 608 bearing and snap it into the idler (best to do this when it is warm, ie put it in the sun for half an hour).
Use 2 more 608 bearings either side of the hobbed bolt.
Add three M8 washers between the large gear and the extruder body.
Use 2 x 50mm long M3 screws, washers and springs for the idler tensioner.

title: Metric Bolt Size Reference for Thing-O-Matic Assembly

description.text:
Keeping track of the subtle difference between M3 x 10mm vs M3 x 12mm can be a challenge on the best of days.  Accidentally mix them up and you're occupied for the next hour fumbling through the pile with a ruler for the closest match.
Save yourself some grief and print off one (or more) of these reference cards to assist with your Thing-O-Matic assembly!
They should cover all the bolt sizes used in the Thing-O-Matic itself, the Automated Build Platform (V2) and Plastruder MK5.

• Pick your source:

    • The LaserCutCoasterReference_Metric.dxf was sized to fit on the "coaster" cut-out in the center of the laser-cut fan filter mount.

    • The ToMboltmatch_4up_v2.pdf should print four laser-cut reference coasters on an 8.5"x11" sheet of paper.

    • The LaserPrintReference_Metric.dxf was sized to fit comfortably on a 3"x5" or A7 index card sized piece of paper or label.

    • The ToMboltmatch_8up.pdf should print eight of laser-print reference cards on an 8.5"x11" sheet of paper.

  • Test-print the source.

  • Confirm with a ruler that the dimensions (in mm) are precisely 1:1 scale. If not, adjust your printer driver's scale accordingly and re-print.

  • Assemble your Thing-O-Matic.

Part to replace a broken impeller from a Whirlpool AWM 6130 drain pump (pump assembly part number: 4812 310 28144, pump proper part number: 4619 710 77501). Will likely work on some other Whirlpool, AEG, etc. machines.
The idea is to heat then fit the new impeller onto the pump's shaft. The pump is still in good working order other than the broken impeller. So before forking out for a new pump it is worth trying to make this, to give the pump some more life. It will likely not work for long.

The thing printed and was successfully heated up to a little over 80° C, pressed onto the pump's spindle and installed. So far it works well, although no washes over 60° C have been attempted. I will update if anything ever needs updating.
"washer thing 2" was used for this. The fit is a little dodgy, due to dimensional inaccuracies in the printer, which if needed will be fixed.
After about a month of use it is functioning fine with all temperatures of wash cycle (30 thru 95°) So I think I will call this complete.

  • "washer thing 1" has holes of nominal shaft dimensions.
  • "washer thing 2" has inner dimensions calculated to be ideal for ABS fitted to this pump's shaft getting a maximum of 80°C water flowing through it.
  • "washer thing 3" has holes reduced by 0.1 mm from nominal.
  • "washer thing 5" has holes increased by 0.1 mm from nominal.
    • This is a tricky thing to get right. It is also possible to use a lighter or candle to heat the pump's spindle up and then press the impeller onto the heated spindle. This could work if the other method doesn't, or your printer is not dimensionally accurate enough.

title: Printrbot Simple Metal SD Card attachment with feet

description.text: Printrbot allows printing from Micro SD cards; however, the reader is located in a very hard to access place. This is a box that clips to the left side of your printer and houses the SD side of a MicroSD-to-SD adapter cable.

You'll need to edit the G-Code of the printer in order to slide the SD card reader inside the box before the printer starts closing it up.
Find the G1 instruction that prints layer 162. In my case (1st layer .3mm, other layers .2mm) .3 + .2*161 = 32.5, so I located the instruction G1 Z32.500 F4200.000. In front of this instruction insert a pause and lift the hot end (lest the plastic on layer 161 should melt) , so your code will look something like

G1 Z42.500 ; lift the hot end 10 mm
G4 P120000 ; pause 120 seconds (120000 milliseconds)
G1 Z32.500 F4200.000

title: Printrbot Simple Metal XBox 360 Power Supply Box with feet

description.text:
This is a box for connecting an XBox 360 power supply to Printrbot Simple Metal. The original power supply cannot supply enough current for connecting a heated bed and Printrbot recommends using an ATX power supply instead. XBox 360's power supply is a great alternative - powerful, quiet, and better-looking than an ATX one. Moreover, there is no shortage of broken XBox 360's out there thanks to the infamous "red ring of death" fiasco. The best model for this purpose is the earliest one, rated at 203 W. This control box houses the connector as well as a power switch and a power-on LED.
Together with my other project Printrbot Simple Metal SD Card attachment with feet, it provides stable feet for your Printrbot.
This thing was made with Tinkercad.

Take apart the console and cut out a piece of PCB around the power connector - the PCB has two large planes for ground and +12V for soldering the wires. You will need to make 3mm-thick plastic washers to use between the bottom of the box and the PCB to align the outlet with the opening and to provide clearance for the wires.
If you only have the power supply, but no XBox, you might be able to make a connector from an adapter such as this one Adapter Converter Cord AC Power Supply Transfer Cable for Xbox360 Xbox 360 Slim.
Supplies:

A PCI Express power cable. Many of the cables out there are just 6-10 inches long and you may be tempted to solder extensions to. Note that it is much preferable to use a longer cable (12"-14) if you can find one as soldering will limit the amount of current travelling through the wires, resulting in motors skipping. You will hear loud clicks, see shifted layers and/or thin gaps in the printed model. Consider getting a longer PCI Express power cable instead, e.g. NEW male to male 6 PIN PCI EXPRESS Y SPLITTER POWER CABLE--12" MADE IN AMERICA or 6-pin Mini to 2x 6-pin PCI-e PCIe Dual Power Cable for Apple Mac Pro Video Card . I haven't used either of those and cannot recommend one definitively. If you find one that works for you, share the info in the comments section.
